496
02:01:08,414 --> 02:01:10,796
Good evening and thank you for this opportunity to speak tonight.

497
02:01:11,617 --> 02:01:17,282
My journey at MVTHS, the voc began in September of 1971 when I entered the school as a freshman.

498
02:01:18,022 --> 02:01:23,387
I didn't know then that 36 years later I would return to teach in the very room that started my career as an electrician.

499
02:01:24,519 --> 02:01:38,502
Now, here I am at the end of a 19-year career that saw the voc grow from a school struggling to survive, where students were looked down upon as not being smart enough for college, to where it is today, a school of choice rather than a last option.

500
02:01:40,103 --> 02:01:42,923
Many have asked me what I like about my job, and that's pretty easy.

501
02:01:43,863 --> 02:01:50,905
Watching a student come in with a dream and leave with a career that I have had the honor of being a part of is the greatest and most rewarding feeling.

502
02:01:51,984 --> 02:02:11,437
being a part of the total re-imaging of the school with my colleagues and their students, projects like the bistro, the robotics and engineering space, and most recently, the new plumbing shop that will open next year, transforming a dark and dingy section of the girls' locker room into a vibrant workspace built by the students for the students.

503
02:02:12,878 --> 02:02:13,479
Point of irony?

504
02:02:13,980 --> 02:02:18,741
My first homeroom in 1971 was V220, right across the hall from the plumbing shop.

505
02:02:19,181 --> 02:02:21,762
So I'm going to start and end my career here in the same spot.

506
02:02:22,942 --> 02:02:28,143
I'd like to thank Bill Mahoney, Roy Bellson, and Tom Ritchie for giving me this opportunity.

507
02:02:28,743 --> 02:02:33,425
And I want to thank Heidi, who held my jaw when I caught a little cancer there back in 2013.

508
02:02:34,905 --> 02:02:38,886
Chad, I want to thank you also for listening and guiding us and letting us do our own thing.

509
02:02:39,606 --> 02:02:43,187
And to you, Medford, thank you for allowing me the honor of teaching your students.

510
02:02:44,085 --> 02:02:46,526
And of course, I have to thank my wife and my family.

511
02:02:49,006 --> 02:02:50,987
This doesn't happen without their support.

512
02:02:51,347 --> 02:02:53,387
And you know, I'm a pretty lucky guy.

513
02:02:54,287 --> 02:02:54,948
So what's next?

514
02:02:55,068 --> 02:02:56,748
Well, in September, we're going to go to Germany.

515
02:02:56,868 --> 02:03:00,329
I'm going to the wedding of the man who gave my stem cells, who saved my life.

516
02:03:01,409 --> 02:03:06,750
And then the only other thing that I'm sure of is that I'm going to be spending a lot of time with those eight humans who call me Papa.

517
02:03:07,331 --> 02:03:08,371
This has been a hell of a ride.

518
02:03:08,411 --> 02:03:09,051
Thank you very much.

519
02:03:15,891 --> 02:03:17,591
OK.

520
02:03:17,611 --> 02:03:18,112
Thank you.

521
02:03:19,692 --> 02:03:22,833
So I'm going to wrap up my career in numbers.

522
02:03:22,853 --> 02:03:34,976
34 years, four superintendents, six principals, four schools, up to 700 students, hundreds of families, hundreds of colleagues.

523
02:03:41,777 --> 02:03:44,498
But one teacher with the hope

524
02:03:46,981 --> 02:03:49,602
to make an impact on my students.

525
02:03:51,562 --> 02:03:56,243
I want to thank my family and all of you.

526
