803
02:32:02,348 --> 02:32:14,415
I made sure that, well, first I will say that when I first presented this, it was tabled with feedback from this body for things to update, edit, and align.

804
02:32:14,935 --> 02:32:16,416
And so, that work has been done.

805
02:32:16,576 --> 02:32:18,698
And what I'm going to do this evening is

806
02:32:19,857 --> 02:32:22,698
review what those updates and alignments were.

807
02:32:22,718 --> 02:32:33,343
I know that you are equipped with the updates and recommendations from the previous school committee meeting on this, which is in May 18th.

808
02:32:33,984 --> 02:32:37,646
Those remain still intact in terms of proposed changes.

809
02:32:38,346 --> 02:32:41,007
And this evening, I'm going to talk about the updates.

810
02:32:41,748 --> 02:32:46,070
So for this evening, the updates from the May 18th

811
02:32:47,651 --> 02:32:55,698
All of the handbooks across the district have been updated so that the way school committee is represented is aligned.

812
02:32:56,158 --> 02:33:14,434
All names and roles are listed as applicable and a link to the school committee tab on the Medford Public Schools website has been provided so that people can learn more about the school committee and know the channels to reach out if people want to communicate.

813
02:33:15,829 --> 02:33:18,391
The second piece was elementary recess.

814
02:33:19,992 --> 02:33:44,852
There was not necessarily an alignment that was needed here, but I think it's important to just recognize that Medford Public Schools believes that recess is an essential component for a child's physical, social, and emotional development and will not be withheld as disciplinary measure for anything other than direct logical consequence for an unsafe body.

815
02:33:46,113 --> 02:33:56,400
That commitment is seen structurally in all four elementary handbooks across three distinct policies slash practices.

816
02:33:57,541 --> 02:34:14,913
One is in the discipline code, which speaks specifically around practices for students' well-being and times when there may be an unsafe body and students may need to take time out to self-regulate.

817
02:34:15,468 --> 02:34:28,631
The other one is under recess expectations where it is explicitly stated that the handbook protects recess and it may not be removed for consequences unless it's an unsafe body.

818
02:34:28,691 --> 02:34:33,993
And then also in homework expectations where the handbooks specifically say that

819
02:34:35,093 --> 02:34:39,774
Recess is not to be used for academic penalties, especially for homework.

820
02:34:40,735 --> 02:34:44,056
Incompletion of homework will not result in the loss of recess.

821
02:34:44,636 --> 02:34:47,897
And then I did say this at the last meeting, but I do think it's very important.

822
02:34:47,997 --> 02:34:51,638
All four elementary schools are responsive classroom schools.

823
02:34:52,218 --> 02:35:03,662
And so this is part of the tenets of responsive classroom, very much tied to logical consequences so that students are able to make connections between their behaviors

824
02:35:04,302 --> 02:35:05,423
and consequences.

825
02:35:06,524 --> 02:35:19,134
But I did have meetings with the elementary principals in order to review this and just remind what our expectations are around recess and the use of recess.

826
02:35:20,535 --> 02:35:24,738
So if there's any further questions on that I'm happy to answer.

827
02:35:25,839 --> 02:35:46,955
The next part was the Cori statement that Dr. Kroll put in her handbook and it is now within all of the handbooks so that regardless of the school, this statement that explains to caregivers how they complete a Cori is now part of all handbooks.

828
02:35:48,848 --> 02:35:58,874
The other piece was around secondary attendance, specifically the middle schools, as there was not clear alignment for both schools.

829
02:35:59,454 --> 02:36:18,465
And so there were a couple meetings had between myself and Principal Tucci and Principal Skane, and a lot of discussion to make sure that we're adding the clarity that was seen at the high school around the time that constitutes what a full day of school means and what does not

830
02:36:18,925 --> 02:36:20,567
like what would equal an absence.

831
02:36:21,028 --> 02:36:27,976
So in other words, students need to be present for three hours and 15 minutes in order for that day to be counted as a full day.

832
02:36:27,996 --> 02:36:32,361
And at the end of this work,

833
02:36:35,497 --> 02:36:49,502
Principal Skane pretty much aligned to the language that was in the McGlynn Middle School around attendance practices and language within the handbook.

834
02:36:50,322 --> 02:36:56,484
I don't think I need to read all of them, all of that language, because it's pretty lengthy, unless you would like me to.

835
02:37:03,427 --> 02:37:04,387
And then after...

836
02:37:05,553 --> 02:37:10,317
this attendance piece, there was the academic dishonesty panel.

837
02:37:10,538 --> 02:37:11,979
Oh, do you want me to pause, Mr. Russo?

838
02:37:13,500 --> 02:37:14,001
Member Russo?

839
02:37:17,163 --> 02:37:17,564
Thank you.

840
02:37:18,164 --> 02:37:26,472
I know when we had met, we had talked about if recess is taken away, that there would be a, is this in here?

841
02:37:28,053 --> 02:37:31,316
That we would, that each school would be logging exactly

842
02:37:32,624 --> 02:37:36,846
that this has happened and that it will be collected by you and all the gory details.

843
02:37:37,086 --> 02:37:41,387
I don't think this belongs in this, but I think it would be important to note it.

844
02:37:41,487 --> 02:37:57,893
I also noticed that under the discipline code section, recess is still listed as one of the lots of building activities, assemblies, intramurals, field trips, extracurricular activities, and recess is still there.

845
02:37:59,474 --> 02:38:01,815
So I'm not sure what changed.

846
02:38:03,490 --> 02:38:08,825
No, because all of the four elementary schools were aligned.

847
02:38:09,761 --> 02:38:11,902
there wasn't really a change in language.

848
02:38:12,383 --> 02:38:17,747
So this piece under the, I would say that there's some repetitive nature to this.

849
02:38:18,327 --> 02:38:26,493
So the discipline code and the recess expectations both are there for when students are exhibiting an unsafe body.

850
02:38:26,613 --> 02:38:33,737
And sometimes that can happen during recess, and I would say that that's part of the recess expectations.

851
02:38:34,238 --> 02:38:38,401
So sometimes when students are outside and engaged in recess, if they have an unsafe body,

852
02:38:39,021 --> 02:38:44,652
They may need to remove themselves from play so that they can calm down, regulate.

853
02:38:47,762 --> 02:39:00,471
is sometimes there are moments where a student is exhibiting unsafe behavior prior to recess and they're just not at a state where they're ready to be with their class as they're going to recess.

854
02:39:01,652 --> 02:39:09,098
And so they may need to stay inside until they're able to regulate their body and then be able to join the class outside.

855
02:39:10,539 --> 02:39:14,962
That all makes complete sense to me, but a serious conduct violation

856
02:39:15,998 --> 02:39:21,362
refers the student to the office, appropriate disciplinary action will be determined by an administrator.

857
02:39:21,843 --> 02:39:34,994
So if a student calls a teacher the F word, what is to prevent the administrator from determining that the loss of recess is an appropriate disciplinary action?

858
02:39:38,082 --> 02:40:04,317
That isn't a logical consequence and I, not that I think it's okay if our students are doing that, I want to be clear, but it just, this is wide open for interpretation and I'm really still very uncomfortable that there is nothing in here that doesn't prevent one administrator from deciding that all kinds of things are reasons to take recess away.

859
02:40:04,787 --> 02:40:12,169
